# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

For negative numbers, we need to insert the digit before a higher digit to get the value closer to 0. For positive numbers, we need to insert the digit before a smaller digit.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

Search for the digit. You can use ascii order to avoid parsing the string digits. We can use `n.as_mut_vec()` to avoid allocating a new string.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(n)$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $O(1)$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
impl Solution {
    pub fn max_value(mut n: String, x: i32) -> String {
        let mut chars = unsafe { n.as_mut_vec() };
        let c = char::from_digit(x as u32, 10).unwrap();
        let x = c as u8;

        if chars[0] == b'-' {
            // Negative => insert before higher digit
            for i in 1..chars.len() {
                if chars[i] > x {
                    chars.insert(i, x);
                    return n;
                }
            }
            n.push(c);
            n
        } else {
            // Positive => insert before smaller digit
            for i in 0..chars.len() {
                if chars[i] < x {
                    chars.insert(i, x);
                    return n;
                }
            }
            n.push(c);
            n
        }
    }
}
```

